tion:underline"> and Public Service Media consumer</span></p><p style="font-size:14pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; text-decoration:underline">Executive summary:</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">This submission addresses the following terms of reference of the committee: </span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">How should the BBC be funded beyond 2016? </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">What comparisons can be made with the provision of public service content in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">other countries?</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">I have </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">3 policy recommendations:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">That </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the BBC should continue to be funded by a licence fee as all other methods are inferior (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">including</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> Finnish</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> example of means based tax funding).</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> (para.1-15</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">)</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">That licence fee evasion should be decriminal</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ised.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> (para.1</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">6-21</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">)</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">That the licence fee should not be extended to New Media Platforms</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Sweden</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">’s example highlights the problems this causes)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> (para.22-2</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">7</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">)</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:14pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; text-decoration:underline">The licence fee: best funding method</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The BBC </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">reaches 96% of the UK population every week</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> with quality PSM</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span><a name="_ednref1"></a><a href="#_edn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">It is vital this is sustained and will require a s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">table</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> source of funding.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> licence fee </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">will continue to provide this. I</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ncome </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">from it </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">has increased by £50million in 2013 to £3.656 billion</span><a name="_ednref2"></a><a href="#_edn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> c</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ollection costs have fallen by £15millio</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">n in 2013, with savings of £220million projected over eight years.</span><a name="_ednref3"></a><a href="#_edn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Moreover in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">2008 study by Human Capital found that:</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">“the Licence Fee plays an important role in shaping the audience’s link to the BBC.”</span><a name="_ednref4"></a><a href="#_edn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The public views the BBC as owned by them and accountable to them due to its direct public funding from the licence fee money. Also </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">because of this sense of ownership </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">pub</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">lic expectations of the BBC for</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> accountability and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">quality of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">public service</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">were high</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">er</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> than for Channel 4, which is also publicly owned, or other PSM producers.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:super"> </span><a name="_ednref5"></a><a href="#_edn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">This denotes a healthy relationship between the public and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the BBC</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> their primary PSM provider.</span><br /><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; text-decoration:underline">Alternative funding options are inferior</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Subscription fees</span><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">PSM funded by subsc</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ription would only cater to the pre-existing tastes of a majority</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and encourage people to only exp</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ect to pay for things they like.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">This </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">lead</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> to underfunding of media with a small subscription base like minority audience programming and stifle</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> innovation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> as producers try to conserve markets rather than risk losing subscribers by being innovative. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Some PSM lacks </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">immediate appeal but yields long term benefits of cultural and intellectual enrichment of individuals and society. These are calle</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">d ‘merit goods’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. L</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ike learning Fre</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">nch in school,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the value of these</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> product</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> is often not felt by the consumer until after its consumption, but it can be significantly life-enhancing.</span><a name="_ednref6"></a><a href="#_edn6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Subscription funding would </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">neglect production of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">merit good</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">such as documentaries an</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">d educational programs, which would severely reduce the quality of British PSM.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Advertising</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Similarly </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">advertising funded </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">producers</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">neglect</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> smaller </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">audiences</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, leaving minorities </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">under represented</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Dr Helen Weeds notes that the reason that PSM was developed in the 1930s </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">was because advertising would not fund</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> high quality or diversity in television, as advertisers value audience size or attracting specific demographics “rather than the value of the co</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ntent to consumers.”</span><a name="_ednref7"></a><a href="#_edn7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In PSM the value of content for the public must be paramount</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, so advertising should not fund it</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Taxation</span><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Taxation funding risks </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">making </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">PSM reliant on government patronage. This is because funding from general taxation makes PSM relia</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">nt on government, who can cut, reallocate or enhance its budget as they decide at any time.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Political bias</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and loss of editorial independence</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> in the production of PSM jeopardises ability to serve the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">public</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">’s interest when it clashes with the governments.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">he logic of not biting the hand that feeds you </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">would </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">inevitably soften PSM producers’ wills to criticise the politicians who control their paycheques.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> It would also leave PSM in constant economic insecurity as any new government may reallocate its budget to other services it prioritises. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">he BBC’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s abilities</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> to guarantee the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">long term provision of PSM </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">provide a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">secure environment for creativity and i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">nnovation in British media production</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> would be chronically undermined</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">The Finnish solution</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">?</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">: Ring-fencing </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In 2013 Finnish PSB Yleisradio replaced its licence fee with a ring-fenced means tested tax collected by the government, calculated per head not pe</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">r household. The 2013 annual report shows the broadcaster has transformed well</span><a name="_ednref8"></a><a href="#_edn8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, but it will likely take several years (and a few governments) to see if the fears of budget cutting and loss of independence due to state control of funding are realised.</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">This</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> submission strongly suggests Yleisradio’s progress is monitored as it may provide a future model to follow if </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> norm</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> of government non-intervention </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and PSM independence is established and sustained.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">If editorial independence</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> cannot be </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">sustained </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">then </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">this </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">will</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> highlight the incompatibility of PSM’s mission to inform educate and entertain with the presence of political or commercial funders. For now the UK should retain the licence fee.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:14pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; text-decoration:underline">Decriminalisation</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Licence fee evasion should be decriminalised to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">prevent disproportionate victimisation of women.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Non-payment of utility bills and parking tickets are both been prosecuted as civil offences for which you do not receive a criminal record. This should be the same with TV licence offences.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">W</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">omen have made u</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">p around 2/3rds of the prosecutions as th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ey are often the ones at home when the inspectors come. Therefore</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> they would benefit directly from this more appropriate scheme of punishment.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:super"> </span><a name="_ednref9"></a><a href="#_edn9">[9]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">  A fine affects the household income, but a criminal record penalises </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">one member of the household specifically, which is unjust as well as disproportionate.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Moreover this submission</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> agrees with the Citizens Advice Bureau in its recommendation that county courts hear these cases not magistrates’ courts.</span><a name="_ednref10"></a><a href="#_edn10">[10]</a></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">It is the non-payment</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> of magistrates court fines for which people are imprisoned, so by moving licence fee evasion to county courts, imprisonment could be avoided for licence fee evasion.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Magistrates’ courts would then be free to commit their resources to prosecuting criminal </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">offences, whereas currently 13% of magistrates’ court cases are prosecuting licence fee evasion.</span><a name="_ednref11"></a><a href="#_edn11">[11]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:14pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; text-decoration:underline">N</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; text-decoration:underline">ew </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; text-decoration:underline">M</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; text-decoration:underline">edia </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; text-decoration:underline">P</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; text-decoration:underline">latforms and the licence fee</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The license should not be introduced at present for NMPs, (computers, tablets and Smartphones) as this would alienate</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> many citizens from PSM, when it should be enhancing access. Currently BBC iPlayer and BBC News Online are key extensions of the BBC’s service </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">which should remain </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">resources</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> which the TV license funds public access to (as it does radio services).</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Every week</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> 96% of the UK population access BBC media.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">It remains the primary news source for 82% of UK adults.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">However only 48.1% of the population use BBC Online</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> services</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span><a name="_ednref12"></a><a href="#_edn12">[12]</a></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Many people need computers and Smartphones for work, but are not using BBC Online services, so it would be unreasonable to pay licence fees for these devices. You can opt out of owning a television, but many people have to own NMPs. For those on low income</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s such as students </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">mandatory</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> fee</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> would be particularly objectionable. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">There is a great danger that extending the fee would also disincentivise consumption of PSM. NMPs are technologically different than televisions, so people can render themselves incapa</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ble of accessing PSM through their NMPs.  </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">This occurred w</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">hen Sweden implemented this policy in March 2013</span><a name="_ednref13"></a><a href="#_edn13">[13]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">a Swedish ISP invented a service to block the PBS content from their clientele’s servers.</span><a name="_ednref14"></a><a href="#_edn14">[14]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The Swedish government insisted that these clients st</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ill pay the fee. I</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">t seems unjust for the licensing system to require people to pay for a service they could not use.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">More importantly even if this exemption wa</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s allowed,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> using these PSM blockers would mean people deprived themselves of the benefits of PSM.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Extending PSM to online platforms should en</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">courage </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">access to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">PSM</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> not alienate people from them.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Therefore </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the licence fee should not be extended to NMPs as this</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> would be seen as illegitimate </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">by many </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and would cause alienation from PSM</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> undermining the BB</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">C’s healthy relationship with the public.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">December 2013</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><a name="_edn1"></a><a href="#_ednref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">References</span><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> BBC Trust Press Release, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic; letter-spacing:-0.75pt">BBC publishes Annual Report for 2012/13</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; letter-spacing:-0.75pt">,  BBC Website, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">(16/07/2013), </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">http://www.bbc.co.uk/bbctrust/news/press_releases/2013/annual_report.html</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> (Accessed: 30/11/</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">2013)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_edn2"></a><a href="#_ednref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">BBC,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic; letter-spacing:-0.75pt">The Licence Fee</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; letter-spacing:-0.75pt">, BBC Website,</span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:Cali